        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-27 13:49:26.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nHere's what I'd suggest: create the clients in the controller, rather than in the provider.  This avoids re-creating the clients with every REST call.  Just store them in a list - no need to put them in a map, unless you want to generate warnings for redundant entries.  Pass the list to the provider constructor.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "40bfd32bda6b203ed787f6b05933fbf738cbfe3f",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 6351,
          "name": "Huaxing Jin",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "huaxing.jin@est.tech",
          "username": "huaxing"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-28 01:19:39.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\n> Patch Set 6:\n> \n> Here's what I'd suggest: create the clients in the controller, rather than in the provider.  This avoids re-creating the clients with every REST call.  Just store them in a list - no need to put them in a map, unless you want to generate warnings for redundant entries.  Pass the list to the provider constructor.\n\nBecause we want create a failed report for HttpClient creation failure for every REST call, we have to TRY to create again for every REST call. If we maintain the list in controller, controller should manage this dynamic list and pass creation failure info to provider.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "be54c050c856ef9194825fc1384cbee6bf65ad75",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-28 01:37:43.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\n> > Patch Set 6:\n > >\n > > Here's what I'd suggest: create the clients in the controller,\n > rather than in the provider.  This avoids re-creating the clients\n > with every REST call.  Just store them in a list - no need to put\n > them in a map, unless you want to generate warnings for redundant\n > entries.  Pass the list to the provider constructor.\n > \n > Because we want create a failed report for HttpClient creation\n > failure for every REST call, we have to TRY to create again for\n > every REST call. If we maintain the list in controller, controller\n > should manage this dynamic list and pass creation failure info to\n > provider.\n\nI think there's a misunderstanding.  Getting an HttpClient has nothing to do with checking whether the other end exists.  Just obtain the HttpClient objects once.  Thereafter use them to try and perform a REST call.  Whether or not it works has no impact on the HttpClient object, itself, thus it can be re-used next time around.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "3d0d439f579b10eafd086b461a4a04eb9a6e031c",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 6351,
          "name": "Huaxing Jin",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "huaxing.jin@est.tech",
          "username": "huaxing"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-28 03:36:23.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\n> Patch Set 6:\n> \n> > > Patch Set 6:\n>  > >\n>  > > Here's what I'd suggest: create the clients in the controller,\n>  > rather than in the provider.  This avoids re-creating the clients\n>  > with every REST call.  Just store them in a list - no need to put\n>  > them in a map, unless you want to generate warnings for redundant\n>  > entries.  Pass the list to the provider constructor.\n>  > \n>  > Because we want create a failed report for HttpClient creation\n>  > failure for every REST call, we have to TRY to create again for\n>  > every REST call. If we maintain the list in controller, controller\n>  > should manage this dynamic list and pass creation failure info to\n>  > provider.\n> \n> I think there's a misunderstanding.  Getting an HttpClient has nothing to do with checking whether the other end exists.  Just obtain the HttpClient objects once.  Thereafter use them to try and perform a REST call.  Whether or not it works has no impact on the HttpClient object, itself, thus it can be re-used next time around.\n\nThat is the existing logic, I am sure about it too. If there's an error to create a client, sending a report with healthy setting to true is also not right, then when and where to convey the message that one client was not created properly? That's why I try to see the possiblity of fast failure if we believe it is a config issue. \n...\ncatch (HttpClientConfigException e) {\n\n                    storeUnHealthCheckReport(params.getClientName(), url, HttpURLConnection.HTTP_BAD_REQUEST,\n                        e.getMessage());\n...",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "2c2a2275e00a1e020d37bca6094f2aab344c0741",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-28 04:05:11.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nif there's a config issue, then the process shouldn't even start - that's how all of PAP works.  Bottom line: build the list of HttpClients once, and then re-use that same list each time a health check is requested.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "b30e6f097f2b4bb2ae01c00bd04baa9f928a6525",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-28 04:06:15.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\n> if there's a config issue, then the process shouldn't even start -\n > that's how all of PAP works.  Bottom line: build the list of\n > HttpClients once, and then re-use that same list each time a health\n > check is requested.\n\nif there's a config issue, then can simply throw an exception from the controller when it's constructed",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "83ec794281544d1689978e716971ebee13cfdcfe",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 6351,
          "name": "Huaxing Jin",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "huaxing.jin@est.tech",
          "username": "huaxing"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-28 05:50:45.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\n> Patch Set 6:\n> \n> > if there's a config issue, then the process shouldn't even start -\n>  > that's how all of PAP works.  Bottom line: build the list of\n>  > HttpClients once, and then re-use that same list each time a health\n>  > check is requested.\n> \n> if there's a config issue, then can simply throw an exception from the controller when it's constructed\n\nOK, I will work on this proposal. And I believe it is a cleaner design.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
